To begin with, I chose attitude, stra and surf as explanatory variables and fitted a regression model(model1) with them as follows. However, as the coefficient of surf is not significant and its p-value is too high, I fitted another model(model2) withouth the variable. In model2, attitude and stra have an positive effect on points. The coefficient of attitude is significant at the 0.001% significance level and that of stra is significant at the 10% significance level. Regarding R-squrare, model2s adjusted R-square is 0.1951, which is a bit higher than model1s one accounting for 0.1927.

Task 3: Choosing four variables and setting up hypetheses

I am interested in the variables, age, Pstatus, higher and famrel. Thus, my hypotheses are as follows: H1: Age increases the probability that a student becomes a heavy alcohol consumer. H2: Living with parent decreases the probability that a student becomes a heavy alcohol consumer. H3: Willingness to take higher education decreases the probability that a student becomes a heavy alcohol consumer. H4: The better family relationships are, the less the probability that a student becomes a heavy alcohol consumer.

According to the tabulations and plots above, it is probalbe that age would increase the possibility that the variables, age, willingness to take higher education and family relations would be associated with high level of alcohol consumption. However, it does not seem that parents cohabitation has an association with alcohol consumption.

Task 5: Fitting logistic regression

Model

m <- glm(alc$high_use ~ alc$age + alc$higher + alc$Pstatus + alc$famrel, data = alc, family = "binomial")

Interpretation

The results about coefficients display that age and family relationships are significantly associated with high level of alcohol consumption, while other explanatory variables are not. Therefore, H2 and H4 are supported by the findings, but H1 and H3 are rejected. In terms of OR, it is concluded that the chance of becoming a heavy alcohol consumer increase by 21.3% as getting one year older and decreased by 23.9% as family relationships are getting better.

probabilities <- predict(m, type = "response")

adding the predicted probabilities to alc

alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)

alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

defining a loss function

loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

calling loss_func to compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data

loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.3062827

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "orange", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0,
         x1 = myscale * heads[, choices[1]],
         y1 = myscale * heads[, choices[2]], col = color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col = color, pos=3)
}

classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

The result of PCA on the standardized variables displays that PC1 explains 53.6% of the variance and PC2 captures 16.2%. Thus, the two PCs explains about 70% of the total varance. As a result, this result is different from that of PCA using the non-standardized variables. The difference is caused by the differences in units of variables. In the first model, as variables use different units, the gaps in their values are large. However, in the second model, as those become standardized, every variable has a normal distribution with a mean of 0.

According to the plot, expected years of education, GNI per capita, life expectancy at birth, the ratio of female to male populations with secondary education are highly correlated in a positive manner, but those variables are negatively correlated with maternal motality ratio and adolescent birth rate. On the other hand, the ratio of female labour labour participation to male and the pecentage of female parliament members are highly correlated but not associated with other variables.

Task 4: Interpretations

According to the result of PCA based on the standardized variables and its biplot, PC1 is involved in expected years of schooling, life expectancy at birth, GNI per capita and the ratio of female to male populations with secondary education, whereas PC2 is drawn from the ratio of female labour labour participation to male and the pecentage of female parliament members. Therefore, it seems that PC1 explains the extent to which a country is developed and PC2 shows how gender equality is achieved in a country.
